The paper deals with randomized algorithms and data structures, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The use of hash functions and random number generators also suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT). The analysis of probabilities and independence of random variables is a common theme in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The study of randomized algorithms often involves complexity theory and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the use of hash functions and randomization in numerical analysis and optimization suggests a connection to numerical analysis (cs.NA).
